// Provide a fix for the buggy function.
Root cause: The issue lies in the fact that the `findAliases` method only checks if the parent node is a `Var` and if the node has children and its first child is a `QualifiedName`. However, this does not cover all cases where a local variable is not an alias. For example, when a local variable is assigned a simple value or a function, it is not considered an alias, but the current implementation does not handle this correctly.
Suggestion: Check for Simple Assignment
Check if the node's type is an assignment and its right-hand side is not a QualifiedName. If so, report a GOOG_SCOPE_NON_ALIAS_LOCAL error. This can be achieved by adding a conditional statement to check the node's type and its right-hand side, and reporting the error if the conditions are met.
// Buggy Function
private void findAliases(NodeTraversal t) {
  Scope scope = t.getScope();
  for (Var v : scope.getVarIterable()) {
    Node n = v.getNode();
    int type = n.getType();
    Node parent = n.getParent();
    if (parent.isVar()) {
      if (n.hasChildren() && n.getFirstChild().isQualifiedName()) {
      String name = n.getString();
      Var aliasVar = scope.getVar(name);
      aliases.put(name, aliasVar);

      String qualifiedName =
          aliasVar.getInitialValue().getQualifiedName();
      transformation.addAlias(name, qualifiedName);
      // Bleeding functions already get a BAD_PARAMETERS error, so just
      // do nothing.
      // Parameters of the scope function also get a BAD_PARAMETERS
      // error.
    } else {
      // TODO(robbyw): Support using locals for private variables.
      report(t, n, GOOG_SCOPE_NON_ALIAS_LOCAL, n.getString());
    }
    }
  }
}
